hands_on_practices.problem:
Consider a one-dimensional, non-linear dynamical system described by the following set of coupled first-order differential equations:
$$
\begin{aligned}
\frac{dx}{dt} &= y \\
\frac{dy}{dt} &= x - x^{3}
\end{aligned}
$$
where $x$ can be interpreted as the position of a particle and $y$ as its velocity. The phase space of this system, the $(x, y)$ plane, contains distinct regions where trajectories exhibit qualitatively different behaviors. There exist special trajectories, known as separatrices, that act as boundaries separating these regions. In this system, one such separatrix passes through an unstable equilibrium point, dividing trajectories that are confined and oscillatory from those that are not.

Determine the analytical expression for $y^2$ as a function of $x$ that defines this separatrix.
